WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

2
00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:24.760
- Maude.
- Oh. Hello. Maxine.

3
00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:27.960
- Hello. A few things for
you here. love.

4
00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.560
'm just
not feeling them anymore.

5
00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:33.760
- Oh. lovely.
- Mm. Italian.

6
00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:36.880
So they should be priced
accordingly. not just to sell.

7
00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:40.000
- Selling things is how
we raise money. Maxine.

8
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.960
- People always pay
for good quality. darling.

9
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:44.320
- Possibly not here. love.

10
00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:45.200
- Ciao.

11
00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:50.720
Hello again.

12
00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:54.160
- Hello. love. Do you want
me to pick up some of that
jam Martin likes?

13
00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:56.280
- Oh. yes please. We're almost out.

14
00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:59.080
- OK. Will do.
I'll see you tomorrow.

15
00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:01.360
- I'm looking forward to it.

16
00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:22.520
- I made your favourite.
- Oh. lovely.

17
00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:03.960
Hello?

18
00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:07.760
Any reason you failed to stop?
- Oh my god.

19
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.200
Constable Haira. please.

20
00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:15.640
He's still alive.

21
00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:18.120
- And her?

22
00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:33.360
Captions were made with
the support of NZ On Air.

23
00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:46.720
- Do you guys want to
see something horrible?

24
00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:51.520
So lame. it puts you off
ever wanting to stay here.

25
00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:55.160
- Well. people don't go directly
to a website to book. do they?

26
00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:57.360
- If you search Blue Motel.
the first thing that comes up

27
00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:59.800
are stories of a dead dude
in a spa bath.

28
00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:01.760
- That will pass.

29
00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:03.960
- The internet is forever.

30
00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.240
I'll do it.
- Do what?

31
00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:08.560
- Turn this crap website
into a good one.

32
00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:13.280
For reasons of self-interest and
saving the job I need to keep.

33
00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:15.280
- Sure. Fine. Go for it.

34
00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:19.520
- Just run your ideas past us first.

35
00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:27.760
- Yeah. I was having breakfast
when I saw this message.

36
00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:30.200
It was from Maude's phone.

37
00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.240
- 'Hugh. we've decided
we can't live with it.

38
00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:38.360
'Please make sure everyone
understands why we did
what we've done.'

39
00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:40.840
What's the 'it'
they can't go through with?

40
00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:41.920
- Martin.

41
00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:45.120
He was diagnosed with terminal
cancer not so long ago.

42
00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:50.840
He has a year. at best. to live.
so I've been helping them
organise their affairs.

43
00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.600
- So. you read the text this
morning?

44
00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.440
- I tried calling Maude. No answer.
Martin ― no answer.

45
00:03:57.440 --> 00:03:59.520
So I just jumped in my car.

46
00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.400
- Hello. this is Constable
Jamie Haira.

47
00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:11.240
- Pamela Owens.
I'm looking for Maude.

48
00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:14.520
Why is a policeman
answering her phone?

49
00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:24.160
- Oh. hello.

50
00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:26.520
- I have a reservation.

51
00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:29.000
- Great. What name is it under?

52
00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:30.640
- You OK?

53
00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.640
- No. no. I'm not.

54
00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:36.040
I've just had some terrible news.

55
00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:45.160
- What are you doing?

56
00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:47.480
- There was a woman crying.

57
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:50.880
- What woman?

58
00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:54.680
- She just showed up bawling
her eyes out in reception.

59
00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:56.640
And now she's checked into Unit 2.

60
00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:57.920
- Why?

61
00:04:57.920 --> 00:04:59.960
- Probably because it's the only
room that's been serviced.

62
00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:01.800
- Saffron. why was she crying?

63
00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:03.600
- That is what
I'm trying to find out.

64
00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:05.600
So. if you just―

65
00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:10.520
- Amateur.

66
00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:12.200
Watch and learn.

67
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:14.600
This girl needs a prop. Wait.

68
00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.760
- A prop.
I should have thought of that.

69
00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:26.520
- Oh. thank you for this.
- Oh. you're so welcome.

70
00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:29.240
- Where would you like these?
- Just anywhere.

71
00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:32.160
- Hey. Is. um. everything OK?

72
00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:34.680
I. um. bought some lavender tea.

73
00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:37.720
The best thing when you're feeling
a little bit out of sorts.

74
00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.320
- 'm sorry.

75
00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:43.160
- No. I can go
and get peppermint tea.

76
00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:45.840
- No. it's just that
my friend Maude.

77
00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:48.840
uh. she always swore
by lavender tea.

78
00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:50.680
- Yeah. She does.

79
00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:51.960
You know Maude?

80
00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:55.640
- Look. I was just pulling in
here when I was told that―

81
00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:57.640
that she's died.

82
00:05:58.240 --> 00:05:59.640
- Maude's dead?

83
00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:02.280
I only spoke to her yesterday
at the charity shop.

84
00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:04.280
- Oh. that Maude.

85
00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:06.760
- Um. the cop's here.

86
00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:09.320
- Suicide pact.
- Huh?

87
00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:12.040
- Do you guys know
Maude and Martin Bromley?

88
00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:13.120
- Only her.

89
00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:15.120
Sorry. sorry.

90
00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:16.720
They're both dead?

91
00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:18.080
- Maude definitely.

92
00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:23.360
Um. Martin didn't look too flash
as he was taken away in the ambo.

93
00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:26.160
Hey. do you remember what you
said to me the first day we met?

94
00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:29.040
- About the board shorts
with the uniform?

95
00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:34.080
- No. about instinct
being number one.

96
00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:36.240
- That sounds like
something I would say.

97
00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:39.320
- Yeah. well. my instinct's
telling me something's not right.

98
00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:40.240
- For what reason?

99
00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:42.240
- Suicide pact. my arse.

100
00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:43.640
- That reason.

101
00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:46.520
- There is no way that the lovely
Maude would have killed herself.
OK?

102
00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:47.520
Why?

103
00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:50.440
- Well. the text said it was
because Martin was nearly dead.

104
00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:51.760
- No. no. no.
that doesn't make sense.

105
00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:56.360
Pam just told me that her and
Maude had VIP passes to the
garden show tomorrow.

106
00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:58.640
They've been looking forward to it.
They spent a fortune on it.

107
00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:01.680
Who kills themselves a day
before the garden show?

108
00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:02.440
But she was fine.

109
00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:03.920
- We're doing this. aren't we?

110
00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:05.240
- I bags the scene.

111
00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:08.040
- Guess I'll take the victim then.

112
00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:13.960
I'll stay in the background.

113
00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:17.560
- I'm cool with you being
in the foreground.

114
00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Mr Bromley.

115
00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:26.080
Constable Jamie Haira.

116
00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:28.000
- Why am I here?

117
00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.800
- You took poison. sir.

118
00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:31.800
- I took...
- Poison.

119
00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:37.520
Where's Maude? I wanna talk to her.

120
00:07:41.560 --> 00:07:43.560
Maude didn't make it.

121
00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:46.240
I'm sorry. but your wife is dead.

122
00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:52.200
- You were both found on your bed.
Mr Bromley.

123
00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:53.160
- Maude's dead?

124
00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:55.920
- From the poison.
- That you both took.

125
00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:57.480
- Why do you keep saying tok?

126
00:07:57.480 --> 00:08:01.000
- There was a message about you
both wanting to end it all.

127
00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.360
- End what all?

128
00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:03.840
- It.

129
00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:05.840
Living.

130
00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:13.840
- Mr Bromley. Martin. are you
saying that you and your wife
didn't have a suicide pact?

131
00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:03.440
- What are you doing?

132
00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:05.240
- Shit.

133
00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:07.120
- Hi.

134
00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:09.200
- You're one of the new
people at the motel.

135
00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:11.400
- Helping the police
with the investigation.

136
00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:13.320
I have a lanyard. Somewhere.

137
00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:15.600
- Hugh Goodall. solicitor.

138
00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.560
- Oh. Vinny.

139
00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:21.320
- I'm just grabbing some things to
take to the hospital for Martin.

140
00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.320
- If he makes it.

141
00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:24.640
- Well. yeah.
You've got to live in hope.

142
00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:27.040
- Still. it's a bad business.

143
00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:29.400
-  found them.

144
00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:32.280
- Did you see it coming?

145
00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.280
- Not in the slightest.

146
00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:36.760
Nobody did.

147
00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:42.880
- I remember Maude arriving home.

148
00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:46.520
It was her day at the charity shop.

149
00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.040
I'd made soup.

150
00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:51.360
She seemed distracted.

151
00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:54.320
Normally. she'd be telling me
all about her day.

152
00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:55.960
The people who came
in and out. and stuff.

153
00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:58.280
But yesterday. nothing.

154
00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:01.880
I remember getting really tired.

155
00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:04.720
Like a wave breaking over me.

156
00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.920
I must have made it up to bed cos
you said that's where you found me.

157
00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:11.000
- Do you remember Maude
coming to bed with you?
- No.

158
00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.280
- I know this is not easy
to hear. but. um.

159
00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:20.000
had Maude ever talked about
taking things into your own hands?

160
00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
- Yeah.

161
00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:23.600
yeah. we both had.

162
00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:25.440
Theoretically.

163
00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:29.080
When you're facing a death
sentence. hard to not have
those conversations.

164
00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:30.920
- And where did Maude stand on
that?

165
00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:36.800
- Well. lately. she started
talking about how horrible
it was going to be for her.

166
00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:39.480
You know. watching me die.

167
00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:44.200
Maybe in Maudeie's mind.
I was already dead.

168
00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:55.400
- Oh. I love your work.

169
00:10:56.680 --> 00:10:58.680
Cheers.

170
00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:04.480
Apparently. Maude was thinking
about taking their own way out.

171
00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:06.760
- Yeah. I found some stuff
about that.

172
00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:10.640
- So Martin survived. but he
had no idea it was happening.

173
00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:15.120
- So. suicide pact out.
attempted murder-suicide in?

174
00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:17.840
- Any news?

175
00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:20.400
- Well. Martin's pulled through.
Which is good.

176
00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:22.400
- What about Maude?

177
00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:23.800
- Still dead. I'm afraid.

178
00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:26.080
- I mean. what's happening? Why?

179
00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:27.960
- There's no way
it was a suicide pact.

180
00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:30.120
- Well. things have
moved on from there.

181
00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:31.200
- To where?

182
00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.000
- Martin says he had no idea
what was happening.

183
00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.320
- So Maude killed herself and
then tried to take him along?

184
00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:38.640
Is that what's being said?

185
00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:40.120
- It's a theory.

186
00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:44.400
- My friend was the gentlest.
most loving person I know.

187
00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:46.400
No. Not possible.

188
00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:50.320
- Calling Maude a murderer.

189
00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:52.000
Wow.

190
00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Poor form. Colemans.

191
00:11:56.760 --> 00:11:58.840
- Yeah. I know.

192
00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.680
- What would you do?

193
00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:16.320
- I knew you were
gonna ask this question.

194
00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:19.840
- So...

195
00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:21.160
if I was dying...

196
00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:24.160
- Well. I certainly
wouldn't kill myself.

197
00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:28.760
- Well. do you want to have a
little think about your answer?

198
00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:32.440
- Well. you know what they say
about fish in the sea. right?

199
00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:36.720
- That they're endangered
because of overfishing.

200
00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:41.920
What if we were really old?

201
00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
- Hmm. I'd still be desirable.

202
00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:48.520
- Well. that is true.

203
00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:51.960
- Go to sleep.

204
00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:05.440
Good morning. Pam.
How you feeling?

205
00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:10.280
- I was thinking about going home.
but I really want to stick around
for Maude's funeral.

206
00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.640
- Well. we're just heading up to
the hospital to talk to Martin
if you'd like to see him.

207
00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:15.080
- Pass.

208
00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:17.960
Martin and I have never
really seen eye to eye.

209
00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:21.160
and I don't think that recent
events are going to change that.

210
00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:22.040
- Fair enough.

211
00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:26.520
- Don't get me wrong.
'll talk then.

212
00:13:28.800 --> 00:13:30.800
- Team Maude.
- 100%.

213
00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:35.880
They're letting you go?

214
00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:39.400
- Oh. Not willingly. But no way
in hell am I hanging around here.

215
00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:43.240
- Fair enough.
Uh. this is my wife. Vinnie.
She's also an ex-detective.

216
00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.240
Also helping the police.
- Mr Bromley.

217
00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:49.760
- Martin. Uh. I already
told your husband everything
'm sorry.

218
00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:53.640
- So. you. um. heading home?
- Yeah. that's very much the plan.

219
00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:55.640
- Oh. you probably
need a ride then. eh?

220
00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:57.640
- Oh. much appreciated.

221
00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:03.400
- So the. um. the wine
didn't taste unusual?

222
00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:09.880
- One of the things about
cancer ― the treatment doesn't do
your taste buds anyfavours.

223
00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:12.160
Oh. After you.
- Oh. cheers.

224
00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:28.400
- What's all this?
- Chardonnay.

225
00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.880
- Oh. Saffron. That's lovely.

226
00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:35.160
Funnily enough.
that is my wine of choice.

227
00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:38.440
- Yeah. I know.
I got it from your fridge.

228
00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:42.760
Well. I need the photos
to look nice for the website.
And you've got the fancy shit.

229
00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:46.720
- Well. yeah. that's true.
but still. I wish you wouldn't
just go into my room.

230
00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:50.320
- How am I supposed to refresh your
towels if I can't go into your room?

231
00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:54.200
- Hey. you know what'd
be actually really cool?

232
00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:56.280
If the towels were swans.

233
00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:01.600
Folded like swans on the bed.

234
00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:04.600
- Why?
- Well. for the website.

235
00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:08.560
When  went to this
gorgeous hotel. and they folded
their towels into. like. swans.

236
00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:10.840
And it was just very classy.

237
00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:13.800
- I could probably
manage a jellyfish.

238
00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:16.040
- Nobody wants
a jellyfish on the bed.

239
00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:18.080
- That is exactly
what I said to my ex

240
00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:22.640
when she tried to get revenge on
me with a blue bottle she found
on the beach.

241
00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:24.920
- Well. OK― Do you want
to grab a drink with me?

242
00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:26.960
I was going to meet up
with Pam at the wine bar.

243
00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:30.680
but seeing as you've opened
up a very expensive bottle
of chardonnay...

244
00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:32.960
- I am on the clock.
- Come on.

245
00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:36.120
Come on.

246
00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:47.880
- Thanks for your help. Maxine.
- Yeah.

247
00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:55.760
- Thanks.

248
00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:06.840
Well. that's odd.

249
00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:17.200
- Martin.

250
00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.200
You're out.
- I am.

251
00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:23.440
What are you doing?
- Uh. yeah. This needs
some explaining.

252
00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:25.680
Uh. it's certainly not
what it looks like.

253
00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:27.680
- Well. it looks like you're
stealing my vinyl. Hugh.

254
00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:33.160
- Yeah. Less stealing your vinyl
and. uh. more keeping your pride
and joy out of harm's way.

255
00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:34.560
- Oh. yeah? From what harm is this?

256
00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:37.680
- Look. you're not
gonna like this. Martin.

257
00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:41.720
Not so long ago. Maude came
to see me about her will.

258
00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:42.680
- Our will.

259
00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:44.840
- Her part of your will together.

260
00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:46.440
She changed it.

261
00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:47.960
- Changed it? How?

262
00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:51.680
- Maude changed the beneficiary
of her half of everything.

263
00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:52.720
- To whom?

264
00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:55.800
- Hmm. Strictly speaking.
I should probably tell them first.

265
00:16:55.800 --> 00:17:01.240
- Given the ongoing investigation―
- We can cut to the chase. Hugh.

266
00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:03.200
- Pamela Owens.

267
00:17:03.200 --> 00:17:07.360
- Pam. the gardening friend?
- Yeah. very much a shared passion.

268
00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:15.440
And. well. I think the reason behind
the change. you see ― Maude felt
that you would die before her.

269
00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:18.040
And she said that when she went.
she wanted this house

270
00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:21.920
to go to someone that
would look after the garden.

271
00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:26.120
- You're telling me that
half this house. my house.

272
00:17:26.120 --> 00:17:27.800
now belongs to Pam Owens?

273
00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:31.080
- Exactly.
I mean. when probate clears.

274
00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:33.440
Martin. we can contest it.

275
00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:37.320
t takes a
really. really long time.

276
00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:40.760
- So what's up with
the records. then?

277
00:17:40.760 --> 00:17:46.280
- He and I. we're both
collectors and. um. look.
I know what it means to him.

278
00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:51.600
- So you're removing them from a
potentially ugly property split?

279
00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:56.160
- Well. I was taking them off-site
for storage until the air clears.

280
00:17:56.160 --> 00:17:58.880
- Even though. technically.
half of them belong to Pam.

281
00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:01.560
- Yeah. well. legally. it's kind
of an intriguing grey area.

282
00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:04.400
- Bull bloody shit.
They're not going anywhere.

283
00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:06.680
You bring them back in here.

284
00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:16.920
Pam's always wanted this house.

285
00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:21.760
You know. she sat at that table.
and said as much on more than
one occasion.

286
00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:24.280
I just thought she was joking.
What if she's not joking?

287
00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:28.680
- So you think Pam might have
poisoned you and your wife?

288
00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.120
- I wasn't here all day.

289
00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:33.480
 went into town to do some
business. The house was empty.

290
00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:39.680
I decanted the wine in the morning
and the soup was sitting on the
stove. It's bloody possible.

291
00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:41.680
And if it wasn't her...

292
00:18:42.040 --> 00:18:44.040
- Then who?

293
00:18:44.440 --> 00:18:46.720
- Pam was on the road on the day of.
getting here.

294
00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:49.720
She said she phoned Maude on the way.

295
00:18:49.720 --> 00:18:54.600
- Maybe she was parked around
the corner. waiting for Martin
to leave the house.

296
00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:58.080
- Why would she stay at the motel
and not here with her dear friend?

297
00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:00.080
- Our awesome website?

298
00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:05.200
- Well. she definitely
doesn't like Martin.

299
00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:14.160
- Website's coming together.

300
00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:15.320
- Oh. good.

301
00:19:15.320 --> 00:19:18.880
- From certain angles.
this place looks almost exotic.

302
00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:21.320
- I will have to take
your word for that.

303
00:19:21.320 --> 00:19:23.640
Do you know if Pam's in her room?

304
00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:26.840
- Uh. no.
She's gone to the pub for lunch.

305
00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:29.000
Did Grace have something
to do with this?

306
00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.920
- With what? And who's Grace?
- The Martin and Maude thing.

307
00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:34.120
And Grace works at the pharmacy.

308
00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:36.640
She's a total keyboard warrior when
it comes to this kind of stuff.

309
00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:39.440
- This kind of stuff being...
- Assisted dying.

310
00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:40.720
End of life choice.

311
00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:44.200
She's always posting these. like.
huge screeds about it online.

312
00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:48.320
To be honest. I've never finished
one because they're really intense.

313
00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:50.320
Hang on.

314
00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:55.680
- I found this stuff
at Maude and Martin's house.

315
00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:57.880
- It will have come from Grace.

316
00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:11.720
- Gidday.

317
00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:14.760
- Hey. I'm looking to rent
a room for a few days.

318
00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:15.720
I'm not sure how many.

319
00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:20.080
- Not a problem. Saffron here
will take care of you.
Welcome to Blue Motel.

320
00:20:20.080 --> 00:20:22.080
- I love the leathers.

321
00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:31.760
- Excuse me. Are you Grace?

322
00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:35.080
- I am. and you're the woman
who owns the motel.

323
00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:39.040
- Vinny Coleman.
These have anything to do with you?

324
00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:41.920
- I heard you used to be a cop.
- I did.

325
00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:46.000
- This about Maude and Martin?
- It is.

326
00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:48.320
- So you're still a cop?

327
00:20:48.320 --> 00:20:50.880
- My husband and I. we dabble.

328
00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:52.800
Did― Did you give these to Maude?

329
00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:56.120
- No. but I have
posted this stuff online.

330
00:20:56.120 --> 00:20:59.440
Nothing wrong with that.
- Didn't say that there was.

331
00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:02.720
Did you talk to Maude or Martin
about the right to die?

332
00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:04.000
- When I heard about Martin.

333
00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.160
Yeah. They were happy to talk and I
was happy to tell them their rights.

334
00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:10.560
- OK.

335
00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:15.560
If you don't mind me saying. you
seem quite young to be concerned
with thoughts of death.

336
00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:17.920
- When you watch your grandfather
waste away to nothing.

337
00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:23.880
begging to end it all.
and being told he wasn't
eligible to go peacefully?

338
00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.880
Excuse me.

339
00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:35.640
- The phone records came through.

340
00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:39.640
On the day. Pam called Maude
three times. but the last time
was when I answered.

341
00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:41.920
so it probably doesn't count.

342
00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:44.280
- Any indication where
the calls were coming from?

343
00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:49.280
- Uh. still waiting on the
cell tower triangulation thingy.

344
00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:52.560
- Hi. Pam.
Do you mind if we join you?

345
00:21:53.080 --> 00:21:55.080
- Oh. Go ahead.

346
00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:57.880
What is this about?

347
00:21:57.880 --> 00:21:59.760
- Have you spoken to Hugh yet?

348
00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:02.360
- Who's Hugh?
- A lawyer in town.

349
00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:08.240
- Oh. there was a message from
a solicitor's office on my phone.
but I didn't get back to them.

350
00:22:08.240 --> 00:22:11.160
- All right. We should probably come
back once you've spoken to Hugh.

351
00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:14.080
- He's going to tell
you that in her will.

352
00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:17.160
Maude has left you
her half of everything.

353
00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:21.440
- Define everything.
- House. property. Everything.

354
00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:24.360
- Martin
must be thrilled

355
00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:26.520
- He was still taking it on board.

356
00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:31.200
- Oh my God. Does that mean that
I'm a suspect in whatever this is?

357
00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:34.160
- No one is accusing anyone
of anything just yet.

358
00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:38.040
- This is brilliant.
This is just brilliant

359
00:22:38.480 --> 00:22:40.480
- I'll take care of this.

360
00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:46.720
- I meant to be at a garden show
today with my best friend.

361
00:22:46.720 --> 00:22:54.920
but she's dead because allegedly.
she had this insane idea about
killing herself and her husband.

362
00:22:55.360 --> 00:22:57.600
And now I'm implicated.

363
00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:02.760
Can you grasp why I might be
starting to be a bit concerned?

364
00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:05.240
Oh. God.

365
00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:08.080
- Was it you who put her up to it?

366
00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:11.080
Was it?
- OK. Martin. mate. Give it a rest.

367
00:23:11.080 --> 00:23:14.960
- Martin. I get it.
You almost died. and Maude's gone.

368
00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:17.240
And now there's this nonsense
with the house.

369
00:23:17.240 --> 00:23:19.200
- Yeah. but you're doing really
well out of it. aren't you?

370
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:21.760
- None of it had anything
to do with me.

371
00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:24.840
- Well. convince your mate here.
huh?

372
00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:32.840
- You all good?

373
00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:36.360
- With a cup of tea
and a lie down. I will be.

374
00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:50.200
- Hi.

375
00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.280
- How did Pam take the news?

376
00:23:52.280 --> 00:23:54.280
- Better than Martin.

377
00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:57.000
There was an incident
on the way back.

378
00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.960
Safe to say. there's no
love lost between those two.

379
00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:01.920
- Enough for her to want to kill him?

380
00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:03.280
- Maybe. but not Maude.

381
00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:07.160
In fact. she seems far too
nice to kill anymore.

382
00:24:07.560 --> 00:24:10.520
- You guys need to get out here now.
Now. come on.

383
00:24:22.040 --> 00:24:23.400
- OK. OK.

384
00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:25.360
- Oh. you just couldn't wait.
could you?

385
00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:27.880
- Get over yourself.
It's in your head. you crazy bitch.

386
00:24:27.880 --> 00:24:30.200
- You'd jump in her grave
just as quick.

387
00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:31.120
- OK.

388
00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:37.360
- That was awesome.

389
00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:42.840
- She has always hated me.
that woman.

390
00:24:42.840 --> 00:24:44.520
- I should have known she'd turn up.

391
00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:47.360
- She poisoned Maude against me.
I know that for a fact.

392
00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:49.320
- She's gloating. I bet.

393
00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:51.840
Finally claiming her man.

394
00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.600
- Martin and I are ancient history.

395
00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:58.400
- Maude knew that they'd been
talking. but Martin always denied it.

396
00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:02.120
- He's a friend. What is wrong with
being here to support a friend?

397
00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:04.960
- I bet he called her
the moment Maude died.

398
00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:08.520
She's always had this weird
kind of hold over him.

399
00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:11.280
- I'm only here because of
what I read online.

400
00:25:11.280 --> 00:25:12.600
- What online?

401
00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:14.920
- That thing that
young woman posted.

402
00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:17.400
The story of Martin and Maude.

403
00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:21.600
- She makes them sound like
Romeo and Juliet.

404
00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:23.960
 guess he does
look a bit Leonardo.

405
00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:26.520
- It's not exactly helpful. though.
- Or accurate.

406
00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:30.040
- Grace doesn't care about accuracy.
She's all about the romance.

407
00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:31.680
Love and death.

408
00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:37.440
Plus. it's the internet. So what
does accuracy have to do with it?

409
00:25:39.640 --> 00:25:41.560
- We've got a passionate
young person.

410
00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:43.560
- With access to drugs.

411
00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:49.040
- Hi. Grace.
Your boss said we'd find you here.

412
00:25:49.040 --> 00:25:51.120
- No such thing as a break?

413
00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:53.760
- We read your little missive.

414
00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:56.960
- The romantic life and death
of Maude and Martin.

415
00:25:56.960 --> 00:25:59.040
- I have the right
to say what I think.

416
00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:01.880
- But not the right to give them
the drugs to go through with it.

417
00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:04.280
-  did?

418
00:26:04.800 --> 00:26:06.440
- You tell us.

419
00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:10.120
- Neither Maude nor Martin
ever approached me for help.

420
00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:12.840
But if they had. I would have.

421
00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:17.640
Any more questions?
- Cos you've got all the answers?

422
00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:23.280
- It's Jamie. Tox report came back.

423
00:26:31.120 --> 00:26:33.600
- I would have said that they
overdosed on Martin's pain meds.

424
00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:38.080
but turns out what was in the
wine was a cardiac glycoside.

425
00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:44.480
something called digoxin
or digitalis or other stuff.

426
00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:47.800
There's a whole list of heart meds
that contain this stuff.

427
00:26:47.800 --> 00:26:49.280
- And it was the wine. not the soup?

428
00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:51.960
- Soup was soup.
The wine was lethal.

429
00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:54.360
The fact that Martin only drank
half a glass saved him.

430
00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:56.160
- Were Maude or Martin
on heart meds?

431
00:26:56.160 --> 00:26:58.840
- No idea.
- It's probably worth finding out.

432
00:26:58.840 --> 00:27:02.960
- Digitalis occurs naturally
in plants like foxglove.

433
00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:06.360
- If you're of
the gardening persuasion.

434
00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:10.040
- So. what questions
have you got for me today?

435
00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:13.880
- We just want to check in after.
you know. earlier.

436
00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:18.920
- Yeah. It wasn't my finest hour.
but I'm sure you can understand why.
- Maude's will was asurprise.

437
00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:22.560
- Utterly. And yet. given Pam.
not. you know?

438
00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:23.360
- How so?

439
00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:26.440
- Well. Pam can be
really persuasive.

440
00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:30.480
- Maude and Pam shared
a love of gardening. yeah?

441
00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:31.840
- Yeah.

442
00:27:31.840 --> 00:27:35.240
- I'd love to see this garden.
- Follow me.

443
00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:38.520
- Actually. you mind if I use
the bathroom? I'll catch up.

444
00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:40.520
- Yeah. Be my guest.

445
00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:14.000
- Do you mind if I take some pics?

446
00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:18.000
- Maude would like nothing more.
- Inspiration.

447
00:28:19.880 --> 00:28:22.160
You. um. spoken to Estelle?

448
00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:25.760
Just arrived.
Old friend of yours. I believe.

449
00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:27.960
- Oh. yeah. A long time ago.

450
00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:32.680
Yeah. She will have heard about
Maude. I guess she'll be in touch.

451
00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:34.760
- Any foxglove in this garden?

452
00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:36.760
- No. I wouldn't know.

453
00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:39.520
- Do you know what digitalis is?

454
00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:41.600
- Oh. I see where you're
going with this.

455
00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:47.360
But the hospital was kind enough
to call me and tell me what it
was that almost killed me.

456
00:28:47.360 --> 00:28:50.280
And just so you know.
I'm not on any heart medication.

457
00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:53.280
- And you have no idea
how it ended up in your wine?

458
00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:54.240
- None at all.

459
00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:56.440
- So. you know anyone on heart meds?

460
00:28:56.440 --> 00:28:57.960
- Hugh.

461
00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:03.040
Although. he'd only want to
kill me for my record collection.

462
00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:09.080
- Speak of the devil.

463
00:29:16.360 --> 00:29:19.000
- Maude business?
- In a roundabout way.

464
00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.160
Hugh just made me an offer
for my half of the house.

465
00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:25.800
- Jesus. That was quick.
- Tempted?

466
00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:28.600
- What he's offering?
Not even close.

467
00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:33.760
- Hey. uh. Pam. as a gardener. do
you know anything about foxglove?

468
00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:35.760
- Not a thing. Why?

469
00:29:35.800 --> 00:29:37.520
- It's just something that came up.

470
00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:39.120
- Sorry. I can't help you.

471
00:29:39.120 --> 00:29:41.120
I'm all about the roses.

472
00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:55.160
- Motive. mean. and opportunity.

473
00:29:56.520 --> 00:29:58.520
- Maude. all three.

474
00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
- Pam. all three.

475
00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:04.640
Unless the phone records
put her elsewhere.

476
00:30:04.640 --> 00:30:08.880
- Hugh? Probably all three. if
he's desperate for the real estate.

477
00:30:08.880 --> 00:30:10.880
- Grace?
- Mm.

478
00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:12.560
Means? Yes.

479
00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:15.560
Motive? Yes. but nothing personal.

480
00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:17.760
Probably opportunity.

481
00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:20.840
- What about our new guest?

482
00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:23.080
- Estelle?

483
00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:25.080
Uncertain as yet.

484
00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:29.920
Martin.

485
00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.680
- It was actually a failed suicide
pact? So why lie about it?

486
00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:36.320
- To make it look like one.

487
00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:39.720
Dying man kills wife?

488
00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:42.560
What's the point of that?

489
00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:45.400
- You're a dying man.
Why the hell not?

490
00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:47.320
- You have a dark side.

491
00:30:47.320 --> 00:30:51.160
- Just one of the many.
many things you love about me.

492
00:30:51.160 --> 00:30:53.160
- Time to stir things up.

493
00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.480
- Yeah. well. I've offered
to buy Pam out.

494
00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:03.840
Just hoping it might help Martin
not having to deal with her.

495
00:31:03.840 --> 00:31:05.840
Poor guy's just got
so much on his plate.

496
00:31:05.840 --> 00:31:08.320
I mean. he's dealing with
his cancer. and now this.

497
00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:13.120
- Not to mention his wife lying
on the bed beside him. dead.

498
00:31:14.360 --> 00:31:17.560
-  did find them.
- You did.

499
00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:20.040
- Why did Maude text you?

500
00:31:20.720 --> 00:31:22.920
- I'm their lawyer.
I sort stuff out.

501
00:31:22.920 --> 00:31:25.040
- But you're Martin's friend.

502
00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:28.400
So why do you think he
just threw you under the bus?

503
00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:31.360
- When he heard it was heart
medication that killed Maude.
almost killed him.

504
00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:34.320
the first thing he said was
Hugh has heart meds.

505
00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:36.400
- You do take heart pills?

506
00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:38.920
- Yeah.

507
00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:42.960
Why did Martin feel
the need to tell us that?

508
00:31:44.840 --> 00:31:46.240
- Look. the way things sit
at the moment.

509
00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:49.440
it looks like Maude and Martin
had this pact to die together.

510
00:31:49.440 --> 00:31:50.920
- Martin failed at his end of things.

511
00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:52.400
- Now he's looking at
a murder trial.

512
00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:55.200
- Sure. it'll probably be
downgraded and he'll walk away.

513
00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:59.400
- But is that how he wants to
spend the last year of his life?
In a courtroom?

514
00:31:59.400 --> 00:32:06.800
- Can you understand. Hugh.
why Martin might want to shine
a little light someplace else?

515
00:32:09.640 --> 00:32:14.600
- Have you asked him about the 50K
he took out of the savings account
as soon as he left thehospital?

516
00:32:14.600 --> 00:32:21.160
And while you're at it. you might
want to ask him why he suddenly
needs a storage unit.

517
00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:22.760
- Huh.

518
00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:24.360
OK.

519
00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:27.520
How about a pinball machine?
- In reception?

520
00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:29.520
Hard no. babe.

521
00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:33.680
Saffron's car smells funny.

522
00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:36.760
- Oof. Do not investigate
the source.

523
00:32:39.120 --> 00:32:41.720
- Oh. hang on. we have movement.

524
00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:48.800
Rolling. Heading your way. I reckon.
- Copy that.

525
00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:54.160
- OK.

526
00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:58.040
He's arrived.

527
00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:06.680
OK. He's going into the unit.

528
00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:11.160
I'll give it a minute or two.
then see if I can get close.

529
00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:22.280
Scratch that.

530
00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:30.920
- Is that what the 50 grand was for?

531
00:33:30.920 --> 00:33:33.240
- Maybe that's why he was hiding it.

532
00:33:33.240 --> 00:33:35.600
Not his first time on a bike.
I'd say.

533
00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:39.280
He was gone about an hour. Back into
his civvies. locked up his toy.

534
00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:41.480
Then off to the real world.

535
00:33:41.760 --> 00:33:43.760
- Hmm. Dead man riding.

536
00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
- So Martin is a biker.

537
00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:48.960
- Just like Estelle in Unit 4.

538
00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:53.120
- To what do I owe the pleasure?

539
00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:55.280
- Just a few more questions.

540
00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:57.280
Nice bike. by the way.

541
00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:01.400
- Oh. I don't even
care how you know.

542
00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:03.880
Yes. I bought a bike.

543
00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:09.080
 miss riding.
so why the hell not take one
last lap around the motu?

544
00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:13.040
- And will Estelle Perry
be joining you on this lap?

545
00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:16.560
- Really none of your business.
- But she's in the picture.

546
00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:17.720
- She's an old friend.

547
00:34:17.720 --> 00:34:23.720
- Dutifully waiting at the motel
until it's safe for the two of you
to ride off into the sunset.

548
00:34:23.720 --> 00:34:28.360
- How I choose to spend my last days
is nobody's business but my own.

549
00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:33.800
Please leave and don't return.
You're not even a real cop anymore.

550
00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:37.400
- But I do know a real criminal
when I see one.

551
00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:51.520
- Afternoon.

552
00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:02.320
Travelling.

553
00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:39.600
Good catch up with Martin. was it?

554
00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:40.520
- What?

555
00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:43.560
- Just. um.
just a few quick questions.

556
00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:47.440
- Starting with are you
an accessory to murder?

557
00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:51.800
Did you provide Martin Bromley with
the pills he used to kill his wife?

558
00:35:51.800 --> 00:35:53.800
- I have nothing to say.

559
00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:55.600
- Tale as old as time. really.

560
00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:58.000
- It's Romeo and Juliet for
the Twilight set.

561
00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:01.520
- A dying man. an old flame
that still burns.

562
00:36:01.520 --> 00:36:02.880
Off the wife. hit the road.

563
00:36:02.880 --> 00:36:05.520
- And down the track. he changes
his will to leave you everything.

564
00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:10.960
- Except Maude blew a big hole
in that by leaving her half of
everything to Pam.

565
00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:12.720
- So. what's the plan now. Estelle?

566
00:36:12.720 --> 00:36:15.560
Now that you and Martin have
had a chance to catch up?

567
00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:16.800
- You're so wrong.

568
00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:20.640
- Oh. hey. listen.
Always willing to be proven wrong.

569
00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:23.440
- I love Martin.
Maude got him first.

570
00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:26.760
Being a dude. it took him a
while to figure out she was
a passive-aggressive cow.

571
00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:29.400
all the time everybody was
thinking she was so lovely.

572
00:36:29.400 --> 00:36:33.320
They were perfect together.
It was the opposite.

573
00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:37.680
I wouldn't be surprised if
she gave him the damn cancer.

574
00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:39.960
- So when did you decide to kill her?

575
00:36:39.960 --> 00:36:41.880
- I never decided anything.

576
00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:44.480
- When did Martin decide to kill her?

577
00:36:44.480 --> 00:36:46.400
- I'm not saying anything else.
I owe him that much.

578
00:36:46.400 --> 00:36:49.680
- Estelle. your pills were used
to poison Maude Bromley.

579
00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:52.480
Whether you provided them or not.

580
00:36:53.880 --> 00:36:55.880
- Just tell us. Estelle.

581
00:36:59.680 --> 00:37:03.160
- Every now and then. me and Martin
would sneak a weekend together

582
00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:05.480
when Maude was at one of
her garden shows.

583
00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:12.080
It was after one of those weekends
at my place that I discovered my
six month prescription ofHerzogin

584
00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:14.480
was gone. along with Martin.

585
00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:18.160
- OK. so did you ask him about it?

586
00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:22.160
- I'm not the boss of Martin.
No. I didn't ask him.

587
00:37:22.160 --> 00:37:24.360
I thought it was for when
the cancer got too much.

588
00:37:24.360 --> 00:37:26.800
Not for when his wife got too much.

589
00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:29.120
- So that's your story
and you're sticking to it?

590
00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:30.160
- Yeah.

591
00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:36.760
- Would you mind repeating it
as a statement of fact for
this officer right here?

592
00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:45.600
- Why is Jamie here?

593
00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:50.160
- Oh. let's just say there's
been a development in the
case of Maude and Martin.

594
00:37:50.160 --> 00:37:54.400
- Well. is it important. then.
that Pam has just left to go
and see Martin?

595
00:37:54.400 --> 00:37:57.680
- Apparently he called her.
Wants to make things right.

596
00:37:57.680 --> 00:37:59.680
- Right.

597
00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:10.600
- Pam. Thank you for coming.

598
00:38:11.200 --> 00:38:14.000
- Always willing to talk. Martin.

599
00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:36.840
- Garden.

600
00:38:36.840 --> 00:38:39.320
Do not drink that wine. Pam! Pam.

601
00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:42.720
- No. I wasn't planning to.
I don't drink alcohol.

602
00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:44.120
- Of course you don't.

603
00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:48.800
- Which you would know if
you'd ever paid any attention
when I was visiting Maude.

604
00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:51.800
- Why'd you take the glass then?
- Because I'm polite.

605
00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:54.480
I was just going to stand here
and hold it.

606
00:38:54.480 --> 00:38:56.160
Just as well. it seems.

607
00:38:56.160 --> 00:38:59.040
- Martin. We've spoken to Estelle.

608
00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:02.280
- She's not happy you dragged her
into all of this.

609
00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:04.880
- I know. She's ended it with me.

610
00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:10.800
We were going to spend
the rest of my life together.

611
00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:16.800
Then I could leave her
all this to say thank you
for being my one true love.

612
00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:21.480
Stupid me.
Living in the past.

613
00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:24.280
- Why didn't you just leave Maude?

614
00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:27.160
Why did― Why'd you have to kill her?

615
00:39:27.640 --> 00:39:30.440
- The rest of the world loved Maude.

616
00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:33.720
But I fell out of love with her
many years ago.

617
00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:38.240
The only time I was ever happy was
when I was able to spend time with
Estelle.

618
00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:41.440
But when you realise
you have nothing.

619
00:39:41.440 --> 00:39:44.600
it's only a short step to
nothing left to lose.

620
00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:46.240
The research was easy.

621
00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:49.440
Estelle's meds seem like the most
peaceful way to make it happen.

622
00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:51.440
- You monster!

623
00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:53.520
- Monster is right.

624
00:39:53.760 --> 00:40:00.480
Sitting there watching your wife
enjoying the dinner her loving
husband had prepared for her...

625
00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:04.680
- And waiting for the
poisoned wine to do its thing.

626
00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:10.400
When Maude started to feel
unwell and took herself
upstairs to lie down.

627
00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:14.000
that's when you knew
your plan was working.

628
00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:22.480
- And there was no going back.
Right. Martin?

629
00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:27.640
All that was left to do
was plant the end of life
literature you printed out.

630
00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:32.640
- Oh. and drink your glass of
Herzogin and merlot. of course.

631
00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:37.480
Bit of a risk
taking the poison yourself.

632
00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:42.320
- But you'd done the research.
Half a glass. No more. no less.

633
00:40:42.320 --> 00:40:45.440
So then you find Maude's phone.
send the text to Hugh...

634
00:40:45.440 --> 00:40:48.840
- And then you lie down next to your
wife. who was probably already dead.

635
00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:51.480
- The whole idea was to make
this look like Maude's doing.

636
00:40:51.480 --> 00:40:53.480
- That was his mistake.

637
00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:55.080
Idiot.

638
00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:57.880
The idea that Maude couldn't live
a day without you.

639
00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:00.080
She was counting the days.

640
00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:00.920
- No.

641
00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:01.920
- Oh. yes.

642
00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:03.160
- Why didn't she just leave me.
then?

643
00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:07.040
- Cos you were dying.
and she's a decent person.

644
00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:09.720
We were going to go to Japan.

645
00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:11.960
Watch the cherry blossoms.

646
00:41:11.960 --> 00:41:14.840
- Murder's never the answer. mate.

647
00:41:19.880 --> 00:41:23.560
Well. enjoy the house
and the bloody garden.

648
00:41:25.480 --> 00:41:27.880
This is Martin. Over and out.

649
00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.880
- Stop! Stop! Stop!
- No. no. no. no!

650
00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:48.920
- Well. that was a lovely ceremony.

651
00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:53.720
- I'm just sorry Martin couldn't be
there to hear how loved Maude was.

652
00:41:53.720 --> 00:41:58.320
- Yeah. And for a dying man.
he has the constitution of an ox.

653
00:42:18.680 --> 00:42:20.680
- Cheers.

654
00:42:21.520 --> 00:42:23.920
- The great work is complete.

655
00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:25.920
- Ooh.

656
00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:29.520
Wow. This is great.

657
00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:32.480
- Saffrom. you have a gift.

658
00:42:32.480 --> 00:42:34.960
- I'm wasted in motel cleaning.

659
00:42:34.960 --> 00:42:37.280
- Your talents do lie elsewhere.

660
00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:39.200
- Oh. wait. Go back?

661
00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:41.200
Aw. Lose this page?

662
00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:44.680
- Why? You both look great.
- No. Delete. Saffron.

663
00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:46.520
- Come on.
You two are very photogenic.

664
00:42:46.520 --> 00:42:48.760
- No. we just prefer to not be...

665
00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:50.160
- OK. well. the website's already
live.

666
00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:52.200
- Nah. nah. take that one down.
Lose that page.

667
00:42:52.200 --> 00:42:54.560
- And then you can put it back up.

668
00:42:54.560 --> 00:42:56.560
- You guys on the run or something?

669
00:42:56.560 --> 00:43:00.240
- Something dodgy. but sure.
Done. Weirdos.

670
00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:03.480
- Not weird. thank you. Just shy.

671
00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:09.840
Half a day. Shouldn't be a problem.

672
00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:11.840
- Yeah. it'd be bad luck.

673
00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:15.760
Nah. We'll be fine.

674
00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:21.280
We'll be fine.

675
00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:25.400
I do not love running.

676
00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:26.960
- Well. it could be worse.

677
00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:32.040
You could be one of the party
animals from unit two last night.

678
00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:37.760
- Oh. No. Ow.

679
00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:39.480
- Sheesh. Who died?

680
00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:41.360
- The woman in Unit 11. actually.

681
00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:43.600
- I'm sure this is not in
my job description.

682
00:43:43.600 --> 00:43:44.600
But I'm so here for it.

683
00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:46.520
- No. no. no. no. no. no.

684
00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:48.760
- Tell me the truth.
Are you guys in witness protection?

685
00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:50.960
- Apparently. you're failed cops.

686
00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:53.120
- Retired.
- Yeah. Retired.

687
00:43:54.305 --> 00:44:54.555
Do you want subtitles for any video?
